## Interesting — Cert Is There But Still Failing 🤔

This tells us the problem is NOT about the certificate being missing. It's about **how the connector is loading the truststore**.

---

## What's Actually Happening

The MongoDB Sink Connector 1.13.0 may not support `connection.ssl.truststore.*` properties at all — it might be ignoring them completely and falling back to the **default JVM truststore** which doesn't have the cert.

---

## The Fix — Force It at JVM Level

Instead of trusting connector properties to load the truststore, tell the **entire JVM** to use your truststore directly via `KAFKA_OPTS`:

```cmd
SET KAFKA_OPTS=-Djava.security.krb5.conf=C:\ProgramData\MIT\Kerberos5\krb5.ini -Djava.security.auth.login.config=C:\Users\G01516271\kafka-connect-test\jaas.conf -Djavax.security.auth.useSubjectCredsOnly=false -Djavax.net.ssl.trustStore=C:\Users\G01516271\kafka-connect-test\truststore.jks -Djavax.net.ssl.trustStorePassword=YOUR_TRUSTSTORE_PASSWORD

SET KAFKA_HEAP_OPTS=-Xms256m -Xmx1g

bsp\opt\kafka_2.13-2.8.0\bin\windows\connect-standalone.bat kafka-connect-test\worker.properties kafka-connect-test\mongodb-sink.properties
```

---

## Why This Works

```
Before:
Connector property → connector ignores it → uses default JVM truststore → cert not found ❌

After:
JVM flag → entire JVM uses your truststore → cert found ✅
```

This is the same logic as how we fixed Kafka SSL — JVM level always wins over application level.

